= section "Introduction to nistuktāb Verbs" do
  %p <i>Nistuktāb</i> (Passive Scale VI) is the passive counterpart to <i>staktab</i>, though not its passive equivalent; <i>staktab</i>, being reflexive, cannot truly have a passive. Nevertheless, it is often known as the “passive reflexive of causative” given its formation. Much like <i>staktab</i>, the meaning of any given <i>nistuktāb</i> verb is generally hard to predict, but this class often includes the following:
  %ul
    %li Passive Causatives (i.e., of <i>'aktēb</i>), but with the verbal arguments switched around relative to <i>'ennuktāb</i>. For instance, the active Scale III verb #{t "αηακήλ", "'ahakēl"} means “feed” (or “cause to eat”), taking an animate direct object (what is eating) and an oblique object (what is being eaten). The passive Scale III verb #{t "εννυηακώλ", "'ennuhakāl"} means “be fed”, and takes an animate subject, as in “he was fed lunch”. The passive Scale VI verb #{t "νιστυηακώλ", "nistuhakāl"}, on the other hand, means “be fed” with an inanimate subject, as in “lunch was fed to him”.
    %li Agentless Resultatives: #{t "νιστυκτώβ", "nistuktāb"} “come to be written down” (*ktāb “write”), #{t "νίστυσαβ", "nistusab"} “come to pass” (*sabb “turn”), #{t "νιστυρ̄σώβ", "nistuřsāb"} “come to be thought” (*řsāb “think”), #{t "νιστυρ̄ούν", "nistuřūn"} “get increasingly hotter over time” (*řūn).
    %li Statives derived from non-stative roots, that is, when a root that describe an actual action (e.g., *bār “cross over”, as in Scale I #{t "ηάβαρ", "habar"} “cross over [something]”) is used to describe a state where no actual action is being performed (e.g., #{t "νιστυβώρ", "nistubār"} “cross, intersect”, as in “the roads cross”).
    %li Many verbs of interpersonal interaction with connotations of reluctance or unwillingness to act: #{t "νιστυσκώβ", "nistuskāb"} “surrender” (*skīb “lie down”), #{t "νιστουτζώ", "nistūčā"} “quit, resign, abdicate” (*wčā' “leave”), #{t "νιστυσ̄φών", "nistušfān"} “admit” (*šfān “cover”).
  %p <i>Nistuktāb</i> verbs feature three prefixed elements (*n-, *s-, and *t-) plus the u-ā internal passive vowel sequence. In comparative Semitic literature they are also known as NŠt-Stems.

= section "Triconsonantal Roots and nistuktāb" do
  = section "The Present Tense" do
    %p The present tense is formed by adding prefixes and suffixes to the stem #{template "*-stuC1C2āC3"} (suffixless) or #{template "*-stuC1C2aC3-"} (suffixed). The prefix vowel is always *ā.
    - alashian = %w(ωστυκτώβ τωστυκτώβ τωστυκταβεί ιωστυκτώβ ιωστυκταβεί νωστυκταβού τωστυκταβού τωστυκταβού ιωστυκταβού ιωστυκταβού)
    - latin = %w('āstuktāb tāstuktāb tāstuktabī yāstuktāb yāstuktabī nāstuktabū tāstuktabū tāstuktabū yāstuktabū yāstuktabū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale V Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "nistuktāb", :eng => "come to be written" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Preterite Tense" do
    %p The preterite tense is formed by adding suffixes to the stem #{template "*nistuC1C2āC3-"}.
    - alashian = %w(νιστυκτώβετ νιστυκτώв̄τα νιστυκτώв̄σ̄ε νιστυκτώβ νιστυκτωβώ νιστυκτωβνώ νιστυκτώв̄τυν νιστυκτώв̄σ̄ιν νιστυκτωβού νιστυκτωβού)
    - latin = %w(nistuktābet nistuktāvta nistuktāvše nistuktāb nistuktābā nistuktābnā nistuktāvtun nistuktāvšin nistuktābū nistuktābū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale VI Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "nistuktāb", :eng => "come to be written" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperfect Tense" do
    %p The imperfect tense is formed by adding suffixes to the stem #{template "*nistuC1C2uoC3-"}.
    - alashian = %w(νιστυκτυώв̄ νιστυκτυώв̄ατ νιστυκτυώв̄ας̄ νιστυκτυώβ νιστυκτυωβώ νιστυκτυώв̄αν νιστυκτυώв̄τυν νιστυκτυώв̄σ̄ιν νιστυκτυωβού νιστυκτυωβού)
    - latin = %w(nistuktuov nistuktuovat nistuktuovaš nistuktuob nistuktuobā nistuktuovan nistuktuovtun nistuktuovšin nistuktuobū nistuktuobū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale VI Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "nistuktāb", :eng => "come to be written" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Perfective Subjunctive Tense" do
    %p The perfective subjunctive is formed by adding a special set of prefixes to the stem #{template "*-stuC1C2aC3"}, namely *vā- in the first person singular, *vanā- in the first person plural, *vatā- in the second person, and *vyā- in the third person.
    - alashian = %w(в̄ώστυκταβ в̄ατώστυκταβ в̄ιώστυκταβ в̄ανώστυκταβ в̄ατώστυκταβ в̄ιώστυκταβ)
    - latin = %w(vāstuktab vatāstuktab vyāstuktab vanāstuktab vatāstuktab vyāstuktab)
    = render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale VI Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "nistuktāb", :eng => "come to be written" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperative" do
    %p No imperative exists for <i>nistuktāb</i>.

  = section "Deverbatives" do
    %p The infinitive is formed from the pattern #{template "*māstuC1C2āC3"}, and the participle with #{template "*mūstaC1C2aC3"}.
    - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μωστυκτώβ", :lat => "māstuktāb", :meaning => "come to be written" },
                   { :name => "Passive Part.", :ala => "μούστακταβ", :lat => "mūstaktab", :meaning => "coming to be written" } ]
    = render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale VI Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "nistuktāb", :eng => "come to be written" }, :forms => alashian

= section "Biconsonantal Roots and nistuktāb" do
  %p Biconsonantal verbs lose their internal vowel, replacing it with /ɑː/ in the present, preterite, perfective subjunctive, and infinitive, /uo/ in the imperfect, and /uː/ in the passive participle. Demonstrated with #{t "νιστυβώρ", "nistubār"} “cross, intersect (intr)” (*bār “cross over”):
